"Grottoli A.G., Rodrigues L.J., Palardy J.E.","Heterotrophic plasticity and resilience in bleached corals",2006,"Nature","440","7088",,"1186","1189",,,10.1038/nature04565,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33646382859&partnerID=40&md5=2974fd14c7242ef49637a2188df9db95","Department of Geological Sciences, Ohio State University, Columbus, OH 43210, United States; Department of Biology, Villanova University, Villanova, PA 19085, United States; Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, Brown University, Providence, RI 02912, United States","Grottoli, A.G., Department of Geological Sciences, Ohio State University, Columbus, OH 43210, United States; Rodrigues, L.J., Department of Biology, Villanova University, Villanova, PA 19085, United States; Palardy, J.E., Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, Brown University, Providence, RI 02912, United States","Mass coral bleaching events caused by elevated seawater temperatures1,2 have resulted in extensive coral mortality throughout the tropics over the past few decades3,4. With continued global warming, bleaching events are predicted to increase in frequency and severity, causing up to 60% coral mortality globally within the next few decades4-6. Although some corals are able to recover and to survive bleaching7,8, the mechanisms underlying such resilience are poorly understood. Here we show that the coral host has a significant role in recovery and resilience. Bleached and recovering Montipora capitata (branching) corals met more than 100% of their daily metabolic energy requirements by markedly increasing their feeding rates and CHAR (per cent contribution of heterotrophically acquired carbon to daily animal respiration), whereas Porites compressa (branching) and Porites lobata (mounding) corals did not. These findings suggest that coral species with high-CHAR capability during bleaching and recovery, irrespective of morphology, will be more resilient to bleaching events over the long term, could become the dominant coral species on reefs, and may help to safeguard affected reefs from potential local and global extinction. © 2006 Nature Publishing Group.",,"Biodiversity; Carbon; Ecology; Metabolism; Morphology; Plasticity; Seawater; Coral bleaching; Coral species; Heterotrophic plasticity; Porites compressa; Marine biology; sea water; bleaching; coral; coral reef; global warming; heterotrophy; morphology; mortality; species diversity; article; bleaching; colony formation; coral reef; ecosystem; endosymbiosis; feeding behavior; greenhouse effect; heterotrophic plasticity; heterotrophy; marine environment; mechanics; metabolic rate; nonhuman; priority journal; species extinction; survival time; water temperature; Animalia; Anthozoa; Montipora capitata; Porites compressa; Porites lobata",,,,,,"Glynn, P., Coral reef bleaching: Facts, hypotheses and implications (1996) Global Change Biol., 2, pp. 495-509; Jokiel, P.L., Coles, S.L., Response of Hawaiian and other Indo-Pacific reef corals to elevated temperature (1990) Coral Reefs, 8, pp. 155-162; Hughes, T.P., Climate change, human impacts, and the resilience of cora reefs (2003) Science, 301, pp. 929-933; Hoegh-Guldberg, O., Climate change, coral bleaching and the future of the world's coral reefs (1999) Mar. Freshwat Res., 50, pp. 839-866; Wilkinson, C., (2000) Status of Coral Reefs of the World: 2000, , Australian Institute for Marine Science, Townsville; Buddemeier, R.W., Kleypas, J.A., Aronson, R.B., (2004) Coral Reefs & Global Climate Change: Potential Contributions of Climate Change to Stresses on Coral Reef Ecosystems, , Pew Center on Global Climate Change, Arlington, Virginia; Wilkinson, C., Hodgson, G., Coral reefs and the 1997-1998 mass bleaching and mortality (1999) Nature & Resources, 35, pp. 16-25; Loya, Y., Coral bleaching: The winners and the losers (2001) Ecol. Lett., 4, pp. 122-131; Moberg, F., Folke, C., Ecological goods and services of coral reef ecosystems (1999) Ecol. Econ., 29, pp. 2151-22